Space story number 1084 coming in three, two, one.

00:09.820 --> 00:18.560
This is the Space Story, a weekly space and aeronautics report brought to you by
this station and NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.

00:21.960 --> 00:32.660
It seems each launch of the space shuttle ushers in a new phase in its expanding
role as America's prime space transportation system. The launch of 41G is no

00:32.660 --> 00:44.320
exception. We recently talked with several of the mission's astronauts. First is
Bob Crippen, veteran of three shuttle missions and commander of 41G. 41Golf is

00:44.320 --> 00:53.480
one of the science types of missions that NASA's doing. As you're well aware,
we're doing commercial science and DOD type flights. And this one is primarily

00:53.480 --> 01:01.780
oriented toward science. It's an earth oriented mission. designed to look at the
earth in various wavelengths using the number of payloads that we have on board.

01:02.080 --> 01:13.060
I think that's probably the main thing that the people of this planet stand to
directly benefit from space is the kinds of ways that we can look back from

01:13.060 --> 01:20.420
space and see the earth. We can learn many things about it, and I feel very
proud to be a part of this mission because of that. We're doing some other

01:20.420 --> 01:29.640
things that are very important. One of them is kind of an extension from my last
flight where we did the satellite repair. We're going to attempt to prove that

01:29.640 --> 01:38.640
we can do satellite refueling. We have an orbital refueling system that is set
up to transfer hydrazine, a propellant, that's primarily used by satellites. The

01:38.640 --> 01:48.560
ORS, ORS, for Orbital Refueling System, is an important test for a possible
future refueling of satellites in orbit. Here is David Leistema, mission

01:48.560 --> 01:57.200
specialist. This is his first mission into space, and he is the astronaut
responsible for the oar's operation. Due to the thermodynamic natures of the

01:57.200 --> 02:05.720
hydrazine as it's transferred on orbit, and because we are in zero-g and there
is no convection for heat transfer, there's some concern that you could get some

02:05.720 --> 02:14.460
hot pockets in the fluid or in the gas on the other side of the bladders of the
tanks and cause some hot spots. And one thing that you definitely do not want to

02:14.460 --> 02:22.460
do with hydrazine on orbit is to heat it up. It's a pretty explosive-type
mixture, so you carefully control the experiment to maintain the temperatures

02:22.460 --> 02:31.560
well below 150 degrees Fahrenheit. And so we will do that transfer in a couple
stages, and we will gather data during that which will tell us how we will be

02:31.560 --> 02:39.780
able to and how long it will probably take to refuel a satellite once we do it
on orbit. Another part of the oars testing will involve an EVA, or spacewalk,

02:40.120 --> 02:50.020
with Leistema assisted by mission specialist Cathy Sullivan also on her first
mission. The primary purpose of the EVA is to go out to connect up the orbit

02:50.020 --> 03:00.080
refueling system with a series of tools that are would be Representative of how
we would refuel satellites that are currently in orbit It's a series of tools

03:00.080 --> 03:09.100
designed That to make connections with the satellite servicing valves that exist
today on satellites that are already in orbit and Part of the purpose of the

03:09.100 --> 03:17.240
experiment is to show that we can actually refuel satellites that Make
connections in pump hydrazine or refuel satellites that are already in orbit and

03:17.240 --> 03:26.020
also to prepare the way to learn the thermodynamics of how we would make a
connection, to design satellites that we designed them and built them starting

03:26.020 --> 03:34.340
today for future satellites to make it considerably easier so that we wouldn't
have to connect up to a basic satellite servicing valve. We could design a new

03:34.340 --> 03:43.520
valve and make satellites much more easy to refuel once we're on orbit. Because
the lifetime of a number of spacecraft is limited by their on-board fuel supply,

03:43.520 --> 03:54.060
the ability to refuel spacecraft in orbit has real economic potential. There has
been some discussion about refueling a Landsat satellite that's up there now, a

03:54.060 --> 04:03.680
Landsat D satellite, but there are no specific plans right now. What I mean is
that there's no mission planned right now to go up and refuel a satellite. What

04:03.680 --> 04:11.200
we're proving on our flight, hopefully, is the feasibility of actually doing
such a thing. And once that's proved, then we might be able to go ahead and plan

04:11.200 --> 04:12.420
to actually do such a thing.

04:15.760 --> 04:25.720
This has been The Space Story, a weekly space and aeronautics report brought to
you by this station and NASA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.

