05:11.940 --> 05:22.140
We recently talked with Alfred E. Mann, chairman of Pacesetter Systems,
manufacturer of medical devices about their heart pacemaker. Mr. Mann describes

05:22.140 --> 05:35.120
some devices which also use space developed technology. We have a device that
uses direct NASA technology in transducers where we use a capacitive transducer

05:35.120 --> 05:46.580
to measure the pressure within the brain from a little, what we call a brain
pill, which is mounted against the dura, which is the tough skin that surrounds

05:46.580 --> 05:55.480
the brain. And by putting this in contact, we're able to measure the pressure
within the dura, within the brain, and to do this all by radiofrequency

05:55.480 --> 06:08.080
communication, so there's no tubes or no wires that come out of the head as has
been necessary in the past. This is very important in the treatment of things

06:08.080 --> 06:19.320
like head trauma where someone has a concussion or something or where someone
has hydrocephalus where their brain does not adjust properly the pressure within

06:19.320 --> 06:29.820
it. The brain pill is an important innovation for health because in these cases,
without detection and treatment, severe damage or even death can occur. Another

06:29.820 --> 06:40.380
modern medical device which appears to have great potential is the PIMS. The
PIMS stands for Programmable and Plantable Medication System. This is a very

06:40.380 --> 06:53.060
exciting device which has been supported by NASA and by the National Institutes
of Health that is a long lived device for infusion of drugs and for diabetes,

06:53.300 --> 07:06.240
for example. The patient simply gets a syringe injection to fill the pump every
three months and he is able to control the insulin delivery within his body at

07:06.240 --> 07:16.840
the moment by programming it, someday hopefully through use of a glucose sensor
to automatically control it. Hypertension, we are now working on something which

07:16.840 --> 07:31.660
we call SAMs, which is a device which will be used in a closed-loose system for
automatic control of blood pressure, for refractory hypertensives, another

07:31.660 --> 07:41.140
important application of the pump. Scientists are now looking at the use of
controlled infusion of medication for treatment of a wide variety of diseases.

07:41.480 --> 07:51.960
So there are many, many applications of this product. We're very excited about
it. In addition to this, we've taken some of this technology and we're expanding

07:51.960 --> 08:03.740
it into a hospital system, where it will be able to revolutionize the way
medications delivered within the hospital, obsoleting some of the current drug

08:03.740 --> 08:14.900
delivery pump systems that are now used in hospitals, it's weighed some of them
as much as 16 pounds, and ours will weigh only a few ounces and will perform

08:14.900 --> 08:25.520
feats far beyond what these older systems will do. These are just some of the
applications that have been fostered by the Technology Utilization Program at

08:25.520 --> 08:37.420
NASA and more importantly by the technology of NASA itself that has been
fostered from NASA's development programs. NASA Technology has made this entire

08:37.420 --> 08:49.340
field possible through the contributions that it has made in advancing the
technology related to semiconductors, integrated circuits, quality control

08:49.340 --> 08:58.300
procedures, reliability assessments, many of the manufacturing techniques and
the technology spin-offs into medicine have been very significant.

