09:49.080 --> 09:59.220
For many years, NASA has been looking at the possibility of flying ordinary
citizens into space. That time has now come. the president recently announced

09:59.220 --> 10:08.260
that a teacher would be the first selected for NASA's spaceflight participant
program. An elementary or secondary school teacher was chosen because of their

10:08.260 --> 10:16.700
ability to effectively communicate their knowledge to large groups of students.
It is believed that this is an important time in the nation's history to

10:16.700 --> 10:25.980
encourage our youth in the study of science and mathematics. Patrick Templeton,
associate administrator for External Relations at NASA Headquarters describes

10:25.980 --> 10:38.040
the program. If this country is going to stay ahead in the world, stay ahead in
new technology development, stay ahead in industry, and new product

10:38.040 --> 10:51.320
developments, then we have to be very well versed in high technology. This
emphasis now on science, math, engineering, and problem solving is very, very

10:51.320 --> 11:01.560
important. The space program and the flying of a teacher can help bring that a
little closer to home and bringing it into the classroom, I think, by flying a

11:01.560 --> 11:11.820
teacher and by bringing that awareness into the elementary and secondary school
levels. Because if we don't graduate more people, more youngsters in the future

11:11.820 --> 11:25.160
who have this this capability, than our friends in foreign countries who are
emphasizing these kinds of studies will get ahead of us. And the new jobs that

11:25.160 --> 11:34.340
will be created in the future, more of those will be created abroad than are
created here, and the jobs for our children and their children will not be as

11:34.340 --> 11:42.840
many as we would like and as we should have to maintain our standard of living.
An announcement of opportunity released in October lists the specific

11:42.840 --> 11:52.140
qualifications and requirements for applicants. said, that process, application
process will probably run through January. We are in the process now of

11:52.140 --> 12:09.100
selecting a procedure to evaluate the applications and we hope that we'll be
through that process in time to bring the 100 or so finalists – two from from

12:09.100 --> 12:19.180
each state and the territories and so forth, to the Johnson Space Center for a
workshop for about a week, and then coming back and selecting, out of those 100,

12:19.360 --> 12:35.700
110 semi-finalists, 10 finalists, we will be taking that down to five and then
selecting a primary and a backup, and those two, we'll go through an eight-week

12:35.700 --> 12:44.980
training at the Johnson Space Center to prepare them for flight. The teachers
selected will not have to be young or even above average in health or strength.

12:46.460 --> 12:54.840
They will go through some of the training that the astronauts go through,
obviously, so that they're used to the zero-gravity environment and they know

12:54.840 --> 13:03.680
how to get in and out of the space shuttle and what to do in the event of an
emergency and a familiarization process with what it's like to fly in space,

13:03.880 --> 13:17.120
getting into the simulator, and those kinds of things. It's not a very difficult
training session, but it's thorough. The health requirements are not terribly

13:17.120 --> 13:31.600
stringent. The eyesight requirements and the hearing requirements and the blood
pressure are not difficult at all, but that person must be able to make use of

13:31.600 --> 13:41.260
the evacuation procedures if necessary. In the future, the spaceflight
participant program will be choosing persons from many other walks of life, such

13:41.260 --> 13:49.400
as journalists, poets, artists, and just plain citizens. Keep yourself in good
health, and you, too, may be selected.

