14:39.800 --> 14:50.620
It may be faddish, but it's a trend that doctors and those concerned with health
applaud. It's exercise. People of all ages are getting into it, and especially

14:50.620 --> 15:00.040
older persons concerned about the condition of their heart. In space, NASA
doctors have had similar concerns. The stress of launch and the unknown

15:00.040 --> 15:09.760
environment of weightlessness have created a need to observe and record such
things as astronaut heart rates. In order to do this in space, new techniques

15:09.760 --> 15:19.120
and equipment had to be developed, some of it just in time for our new national
consciousness of health. Here to discuss several of their new health products is

15:19.120 --> 15:28.500
Dick Sharnytsky, President of Heart Rate Incorporated. One is a heart rate
monitor that is used to monitor the heart rate of people that are working out in

15:28.500 --> 15:39.200
health clubs, gymnasiums, to determine whether their heart rate is at its proper
training level. The sensors that are used in this heart rate monitor came from

15:39.200 --> 15:49.520
NASA, and that's the reason that we're at this technology utilization conference
is to show how NASA has helped us with this product. The other product that we

15:49.520 --> 15:58.800
have is called a VersaClimber. It is a full body exercise machine. You
essentially climb on this device. You stand on two foot pedals, and you hold on

15:58.800 --> 16:09.300
the two hand grips, and your arms and legs are oscillating in a climbing motion
as if you were climbing a ladder. It's a very high-level exercise activity. So,

16:09.380 --> 16:20.120
basically then, with the aerobic exercise on the VersaClimber and the heart rate
monitor to determine which level you're at. It makes a complementary combination

16:20.120 --> 16:31.460
of the products. NASA has an ongoing program to help businesses large and small
find application for NASA developed technology. Data bank centers located

16:31.460 --> 16:41.400
throughout the nation are a good example. One such center is called the Westrack
facility. Through the Westrack facility at the University of Southern

16:41.400 --> 16:52.300
California, we found a patent that NASA had on an ECG, or biomedical sensor, and
we were looking for a sensor that would accomplish some tasks that present

16:52.300 --> 17:04.540
technology would not accomplish. And when we found this patent in the USC data
bank, we then contacted NASA, and they supplied us with a license on that

17:04.540 --> 17:13.500
sensor. And the sensor is what you see in this unit. It allows us to pick up
these biomedical signals and do a much better job than other products. Often one

17:13.500 --> 17:24.160
product leads to another. The heart rate monitor is no exception. There are a
number of other products which will eventually be developed, either by ourselves

17:24.160 --> 17:34.840
or in conjunction with other companies, to utilize this new technology. And
those include stress testing. This product can be miniaturized and put in a

17:34.840 --> 17:43.660
heart rate wristwatch so that you can wear the device on your wrist so that a
jogger, for instance, might use it. It can be used in Holter Monitoring, which

17:43.660 --> 17:55.420
is a method of... You essentially carry a tape recorder around on your body, and
the sensors are picking up your ECG activity on a continuous basis. Then when

17:55.420 --> 18:04.540
you go back to the doctor's office, it's analyzed diagnostically to determine
your condition. Another future application could be an ECG screening. That is

18:04.540 --> 18:15.120
where you're being screened on maybe a two- to three-minute hookup to determine
roughly the condition of your cardiovascular system. Right now, the way that's

18:15.120 --> 18:22.960
normally done is they use disposable electrodes. Three disposable electrodes are
attached to a person. They cost about a dollar and a half, and within three

18:22.960 --> 18:29.920
minutes, they're thrown away. So that every three minutes, it's costing
approximately a dollar and a half. In this case, these are permanent sensors.

18:30.240 --> 18:39.220
You use them and reuse them, so that in screening, you can see that at the end
of a day, you can save a considerable number of dollars in not having used all

18:39.220 --> 18:40.340
of these disposable sensors.

